.TH KALK 1 "2026-03-15" "kalk" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
kalk \- a terminal spreadsheet with colors, formulas, and sorting
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B kalk
.RI [ file.csv ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B kalk
is a minimal VisiCalc-inspired spreadsheet for the terminal.
It reads and writes CSV files and supports formulas with 47 functions,
cell colors (foreground and background), bold/italic text, conditional
formatting, row/column operations, data sorting, cell replication with
relative reference adjustment, frozen title rows/columns,
multi-sheet support with cross-sheet references, undo/redo,
and formula autocomplete.
.PP
Supports both traditional (@SUM(A1...A4)) and Google Sheets-style
(=SUM(A1:A4)) formula syntax. Multi-argument functions, SUMIF/COUNTIF
with conditions, and VLOOKUP/HLOOKUP are also supported.
.PP
The grid supports columns A\-IV (256) and rows 1\-1024.
.SH NAVIGATION
.TP
.B Arrow keys
Move cursor
.TP
.B Tab
Move to next column
.TP
.B Enter
Move to next row
.TP
.B Home
Jump to cell A1 (or first unlocked cell)
.TP
.B >
Go to a specific cell (type reference, e.g. B12)
.SH ENTERING DATA
.PP
Type a number, formula, or label directly. Formulas start with
.BR + \fR, \fB \- \fR, \fB ( \fR, \fB @ \fR, or \fB = .
Labels can be entered directly or prefixed with
.BR \(dq .
.TP
.B Backspace/Delete
Clear current cell
.TP
.B !
Force recalculation
.TP
.B Ctrl+Z
Undo last operation (also available in command mode)
.TP
.B Ctrl+Y
Redo last undo (also available in command mode)
.TP
.B Ctrl+C
Quit
.TP
.B Tab / Up / Down
Navigate autocomplete suggestions while typing formulas
.SH FORMULAS
.PP
Formulas support arithmetic operators (+, \-, *, /), comparison operators
(<, >, <=, >=, =, <>, !=), parentheses, cell references (e.g. A1, $B$2),
and functions:
.SS Range and aggregate functions
.TP
.B @SUM(range|args)
Sum of values in range or comma-separated list (e.g. @SUM(A1...A10)
or =SUM(A1, A2, A3))
.TP
.B @AVERAGE(range|args)
Mean of values in range or comma-separated list
.TP
.B @MIN(range|args)
Minimum value in range or comma-separated list
.TP
.B @MAX(range|args)
Maximum value in range or comma-separated list
.TP
.B @COUNT(range|args)
Count of numeric cells in range or comma-separated list
.SS Conditional functions
.TP
.B @SUMIF(range, condition, [sum_range])
Sum cells in range matching condition. Optionally sum a different
range: =SUMIF(A1:A10, ">5", B1:B10)
.TP
.B @COUNTIF(range, condition)
Count cells in range matching condition. Conditions use the same
operators as comparisons: >5, <0, >=10, <=3, =42, <>7, or plain 5
.SS Lookup functions
.TP
.B @VLOOKUP(key, range, col_index, [is_sorted])
Search first column of range for exact key match, return value from
indexed column (1-based). Optional is_sorted argument is accepted but
ignored (always exact match).
.TP
.B @HLOOKUP(key, range, row_index, [is_sorted])
Search first row of range for exact key match, return value from
indexed row (1-based).
.SS Text functions
.TP
.B @LEN(expr)
Length of a string (accepts cell ref, string literal, or expression)
.TP
.B @FIND(substring, str)
Position of substring in str (1-indexed). Returns NAN if not found.
.TP
.B @LEFT(str, n)
First n characters of str
.TP
.B @RIGHT(str, n)
Last n characters of str
.TP
.B @MID(str, start, n)
Substring starting at position (1-indexed), n characters long
.TP
.B @UPPER(str)
Convert string to uppercase (returns string cell value)
.TP
.B @LOWER(str)
Convert string to lowercase (returns string cell value)
.TP
.B @TRIM(str)
Remove leading and trailing whitespace (returns string cell value)
.TP
.B @CONCATENATE(str1, str2, ...)
Join strings together (returns string cell value)
.PP
String arguments can be cell references (A1), string literals (\(dq hello\(dq),
or expressions. Functions that return strings (UPPER, LOWER, TRIM, LEFT,
RIGHT, MID, CONCATENATE) produce a string cell value. Functions that accept
strings (LEN, FIND) also accept numeric values (converted automatically).
Text functions can be nested: LEN(UPPER(A1)) returns the length of the
uppercased value of A1.
.SS Date/time functions
.TP
.B @DATE(year, month, day)
Create a date serial from year, month, and day values
.TP
.B @TODAY()
Current date as a serial number
.TP
.B @NOW()
Current date and time as a serial number
.TP
.B @YEAR(serial)
Extract year from a date serial
.TP
.B @MONTH(serial)
Extract month (1-12) from a date serial
.TP
.B @DAY(serial)
Extract day of month (1-31) from a date serial
.TP
.B @HOUR(serial)
Extract hour (0-23) from a date serial
.TP
.B @MINUTE(serial)
Extract minute (0-59) from a date serial
.TP
.B @SECOND(serial)
Extract second (0-59) from a date serial
.TP
.B @WEEKDAY(serial, [type])
Day of week. type=1 (default): Sun=1..Sat=7, type=2: Mon=1..Sun=7,
type=3: Mon=0..Sun=6
.TP
.B @DATEDIF(start, end, unit)
Difference between dates. Units: "Y" (years), "M" (months),
"D" (days), "MD" (days ignoring months), "YM" (months ignoring years),
"YD" (days ignoring years)
.PP
Date serials are days since 1970-01-01. When you type a date like
2024-01-15 or 1/15/2024, kalk auto-detects it and stores the serial
with format set to 'T'. Date arithmetic works naturally: A1+7 on a
date cell shifts it by 7 days. The date picker popup (/F P) provides
a visual calendar for selecting dates.
.PP
Cell formats for date/time display:
T = YYYY-MM-DD (with time if present), U = MM/DD/YYYY,
u = DD-Mon-YYYY, t = HH:MM:SS (time only),
S = HH:MM:SS (duration from serial, e.g. 1.5 -> 36:00:00)
.SS Math and utility functions
.TP
.B @IF(cond, tval, fval)
If cond is non-zero and not NAN, returns tval, else fval
.TP
.B @ABS(expr)
Absolute value
.TP
.B @INT(expr)
Integer part (truncate)
.TP
.B @SQRT(expr)
Square root
.TP
.B @ROUND(expr, places)
Round to N decimal places (default 0)
.TP
.B @ROUNDUP(expr, places)
Round up to N decimal places (default 0)
.TP
.B @ROUNDDOWN(expr, places)
Round down to N decimal places (default 0)
.TP
.B @CEILING(expr)
Round up to nearest integer
.TP
.B @FLOOR(expr)
Round down to nearest integer
.TP
.B @POWER(expr, exp)
Raise to a power (e.g. POWER(2, 3)=8)
.TP
.B @MOD(expr, divisor)
Modulo (remainder)
.TP
.B @PI()
The constant &pi (~3.14159)
.TP
.B @RAND()
Random number in [0, 1)
.TP
.B @RANDBETWEEN(a, b)
Random integer in [a, b]
.TP
.B @SIN(expr)
Sine (radians)
.TP
.B @COS(expr)
Cosine (radians)
.TP
.B @TAN(expr)
Tangent (radians)
.TP
.B @LOG(expr)
Natural logarithm
.PP
Functions can be used with or without the @ prefix (e.g. SUM(A1:A10)
works the same as @SUM(A1:A10)). SUM/AVERAGE/MIN/MAX/COUNT accept both
ranges (A1:A10) and comma-separated lists (A1, A2, A3). Ranges can use
either
.B ...
(e.g. A1...A10) or
.B :
(e.g. A1:A10).
.PP
Cell references can use
.B $
to mark absolute columns or rows:
.B $A1
(absolute column),
.B A$1
(absolute row),
.B $A$1
(both).
Absolute references are preserved during replicate operations.
.SH COMMANDS
.PP
Press
.B /
to enter command mode. Available commands:
.TP
.B /A
Auto-fill patterns downward or rightward. Choose direction (D/R), then
the number of cells to fill. Seeds are detected automatically from
cells above (for down) or left (for right). Supports linear arithmetic
sequences (1, 2, 3...), day names (Mon, Tue, Wed...), month names
(Jan, Feb, Mar...), and simple copy/tiling for other values.
.TP
.B /B
Blank current cell (clear value, keep format)
.TP
.B /C
Clear entire spreadsheet
.TP
.B /D R\fR,\fB /D C
Delete current row or column
.TP
.B /I R\fR,\fB /I C
Insert row or column at cursor
.TP
.B /F \fIformat\fR
Set cell format: L(eft) R(ight) I(nteger) G(eneral) D(efault)
$(dollar) %(percent) *(bar graph) T(date) U(US date)
u(DD-Mon-YYYY) t(time) S(duration HH:MM:SS)
.TP
.B /F C
Set foreground color (0=blk, 1=Red, 2=Grn, 3=Yel, 4=Blu, 5=Mag,
6=Cyn, 7=Wht)
.TP
.B /F B
Set background color (same palette as foreground)
.TP
.B /F O
Set text attribute (0=none, 1=Bold, 2=Italic, 3=Both)
.TP
.B /F N
Set conditional format rule (e.g. >5, <0, =10, <>7). Enter=clear.
The cell is colored with its assigned color only when the rule matches.
.TP
.B /F X
Clear all cell formatting: foreground/background color, text attribute,
and conditional format rule
.TP
.B /F P
Date picker popup - a mini calendar to visually select a date.
Use arrow keys to navigate, Tab to switch field (day/month/year),
Enter to select, Esc to cancel.
.TP
.B /GC
Set global column width (4\-20)
.TP
.B /GF \fIformat\fR
Set global default format
.TP
.B /M
Move row or column (use arrow keys to drag, Enter to confirm,
Esc to cancel)
.TP
.B /O
Sort rows ascending by column. Type a column letter (e.g. A, B, AA).
Labels and empty cells sink to bottom.
.TP
.B /R
Replicate (copy) cells. Select source range (arrow keys or type ref,
Enter to confirm, Esc to cancel), then pick target location. Formulas
adjust relative references automatically.
.TP
.B /E
Sheet explorer - show all sheets, type a number to switch
.TP
.B /N
Next sheet
.TP
.B /P
Previous sheet
.TP
.B /W E
New sheet (prompt for name)
.TP
.B /W R
Rename current sheet
.TP
.B /W D
Delete current sheet (cannot delete the last sheet)
.TP
.B /W I
Import CSV file into a new sheet (sheet named after the filename)
.TP
.B /W L\fR/\fB R
Move current sheet tab left or right (reorder tabs)
.TP
.B /W C
Set current sheet tab color (0-7 palette)
.TP
.B /Y
Yank (copy) selected cells to clipboard
.TP
.B /X
Cut selected cells to clipboard (yank + clear)
.TP
.B /V
Paste cells from clipboard
.TP
.B /SL
Load CSV file
.TP
.B /SS
Save CSV file
.TP
.B /SQ
Save and quit
.TP
.B /TV\fR,\fB /TH\fR,\fB /TB\fR,\fB /TN
Lock title rows/columns: Vertical (freeze columns left of cursor),
Horizontal (freeze rows above cursor), Both, or None
.TP
.B /Q
Quit (prompts if unsaved changes)
.SS Cross-sheet references
.PP
Formulas can reference cells on other sheets using the
.I SheetName!CellRef
syntax. For example, `=Sheet2!A1+5` adds 5 to the value of cell A1 on Sheet2.
Sheet names are matched case-insensitively.
.PP
Copy/paste between sheets: yank or cut cells from one sheet, navigate
(/N, /P, or /E) to another sheet, and paste with /V.
.SS Formula autocomplete
.PP
While typing a formula in entry mode, kalk shows a popup with matching
function names. Use
.B Tab
or
.B Up/Down
arrows to cycle through suggestions,
.B Enter
to accept. The popup shows the function signature (argument hints)
and a description of what the function does. Fuzzy matching allows
typing partial names like "rou" to match ROUND, ROUNDUP, and ROUNDDOWN.
Recently used functions are ranked higher in the suggestions.
Adjacent cell ranges are also suggested (e.g. when typing SUM(,
kalk suggests nearby data ranges).
.SH FILES
.PP
kalk reads and writes standard CSV files. Formulas are stored as entered
(e.g. +A1+B1) and recalculated on load.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Normal exit
.TP
.B 1
Error (e.g. failed to load file)
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B kalk
Start with an empty spreadsheet
.TP
.B kalk budget.csv
Open an existing CSV file
